06494nam a22008055i 9780774829656DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748296567 a10.59962/97807748296562doi  a(DE-B1597)662133  a(OCoLC)912021598  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a330.9/05122300aAfter '08 :bSocial Policy and the Global Financial Crisis /ced. by Gerard W. Boychuk, Stephen McBride, Rianne Mahon. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b1 map, 12 graphs, 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tContext -- tNeo-Liberalism in Question? -- tBroadening the Frame -- tA New Era for Social Policy? -- tInternational Organizations -- tUnderstanding Policy Change as Position-Taking -- tThe ILO and Social Protection Policy after the Global Financial Crisis -- tThe ILO, Greece, and Social Dialogue in the Aftermath of the GFC -- tIt Takes Two to Tango -- tEmerging Areas -- tIntegrating the Social into CEPAL’s Neo-Structuralist Discourse -- tThe Impact of the Global Financial Crisis on Mexican Social Policy -- tSocial Policy in South Africa -- tIn the Shadow of Crisis -- tGlobal North -- tGlobal Crisis and Social Policy in Peripheral Europe -- tAusterity Budgets and Public Sector Retrenchment -- tAusterity Lite -- tUS Incremental Social Policy Expansionism in Response to Crisis -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 2007-08 financial crisis marked a turning point for social policy. World leaders were forced to take a position: Should they entrench neo-liberal policies in response to the crisis? Or should they implement alternative measures to challenge economics as usual? After '08 examines how global institutions, such as the World Bank, International Monetary Fund, and International Labour Organization, as well as nation states around the world responded to the crisis. Comparing the experience of Europe, Asia, Africa, Latin America, and North America, contributors gauge the extent to which the neo-liberal landscape has shifted since the onset of the financial crisis and explore the directions social policy has taken. Did the response to the crisis follow a similar trajectory across countries and regions? Or did the diversity in national experiences produce a diversity of policy responses? And, if so, where did alternatives to neo-liberalism emerge?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009 - Political aspects. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009--Social aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aAyhan, Berkay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoychuk, Gerard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoychuk, Gerard W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClarke, Marlea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeacon, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarnsworth, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaworth, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrving, Zoë, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenson, Jane, ec